{"add":{"doc":{"id":"b8e6bfca00bc2a1f66d6155c83c362f97cfae0c181ff90ab998ac506268d1616","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/91/Kituwah_Academy.png/220px-Kituwah_Academy.png","previous":[],"after":["One of the more widely accepted definitions of a native speaker is someone who was born in a particular country and was raised to speak the language of that country during the critical period of their development,[3] The journal or qualifies as a \"native speaker\" of a language if they were born and immersed in the language during youth, in a family where the adults shared a similar language experience as the child.[4] Native speakers are considered to be an authority on their given language due to their natural acquisition process regarding the language, versus having learned the language later in life. This is achieved through personal interaction with the language and speakers of the language. Native speakers will not necessarily be knowledgeable about every grammatical rule of the language, but will have good \"intuition\" of the rules through their experience with the language.[4]"]}}}